---
/* Comprehensive historical profile of Father Seraphim Rose. Rendered by
   witness/[slug].astro for the "seraphim-rose" slug in place of the simple
   memorial template. Data + citations live in src/lib/seraphim.ts. Reverent,
   factual, encyclopedic tone; no canonical/veneration framing (he is not
   glorified). */
import { withBase } from "../lib/format";
import { saintAvatar } from "../lib/icons";
import EyebrowRule from "./EyebrowRule.astro";
import type { Witness } from "../lib/witnesses";
import {
  SERAPHIM_LIFE_TIMELINE,
  SERAPHIM_WORKS,
  SERAPHIM_BOOKS_ABOUT,
  SERAPHIM_QUOTES,
  SERAPHIM_RELATED,
  SERAPHIM_AMERICA_TIMELINE,
  SERAPHIM_GALLERY,
  SERAPHIM_SOURCES,
} from "../lib/seraphim";

const { w } = Astro.props as { w: Witness };
const portrait = saintAvatar({ name: w.name }, 120, 148, { awaiting: true });

const themes = [...new Set(SERAPHIM_QUOTES.map((q) => q.theme))];
const quotesByTheme = themes.map((t) => ({
  theme: t,
  items: SERAPHIM_QUOTES.filter((q) => q.theme === t),
}));

const THEMES = [
  "Modern secularism",
  "Nihilism",
  "Spiritual warfare",
  "Orthodox spirituality",
  "The afterlife",
  "The modern religious landscape",
  "Patristic Christianity",
];
---

<article class="sr">
  {/* back bar */}
  <div class="sr-back">
    <a href={withBase("america")} class="sr-back-link">
      <svg
        width="16"
        height="16"
        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
        fill="none"
        stroke="currentColor"
        stroke-width="1.7"
        stroke-linecap="round"
        stroke-linejoin="round"
        aria-hidden="true"><path d="M14 6l-6 6 6 6"></path></svg
      >
      Back to Saints of America
    </a>
  </div>

  {/* head */}
  <header class="sr-head">
    <div class="sr-portrait" set:html={portrait} />
    <div class="sr-headtext">
      <EyebrowRule label="A Witness of Our Time" />
      <h1 class="sr-name">{w.name}</h1>
      <p class="sr-epithet">{w.epithet}</p>
      <div class="sr-meta">
        <span class="sr-role">{w.role}</span>
        <span class="sr-dot"></span>
        <span class="sr-years">1934 &ndash; 1982</span>
      </div>
      <p class="sr-place">{w.place}</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="sr-notice">
    <strong>Not yet glorified</strong> &mdash; held in the living memory of the faithful.
    Father Seraphim is remembered with love and gratitude, but is not (or not yet)
    formally glorified by the Church. No feast, liturgical veneration, or intercession
    is implied here; what follows is an historical profile, subject to clergy and
    source review.
  </div>

  {/* OVERVIEW */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim Rose (born Eugene Dennis Rose) was an American convert,
      monk, and writer of the Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia (ROCOR)
      who, with Gleb Podmoshensky (later Fr Herman), built one of the most
      widely-read bodies of English-language Orthodox literature of the
      twentieth century. He was born on August 13, 1934, in San Diego,
      California, into a Protestant family.
    </p>
    <p>
      A gifted student, he graduated from Pomona College in 1956 and pursued the
      study of philosophy, Chinese language, and Eastern religions, taking an
      M.A. in Oriental Languages at the University of California, Berkeley
      (1961) and studying Chinese under the scholar Gi-ming Shien. After a
      period of atheism and disillusionment with modern secular culture, he
      encountered Russian Orthodoxy in San Francisco and was received into the
      Church by chrismation in 1962, coming under the guidance of <strong
        >St John Maximovitch</strong
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      With Gleb Podmoshensky he founded the St Herman of Alaska Brotherhood
      (1963) and its publishing work — the magazine The Orthodox Word and St
      Herman Press (1965). In 1969 the brotherhood withdrew to the wilderness
      near Platina, California; Eugene was tonsured a monk with the name
      Seraphim (after St Seraphim of Sarov), and was ordained a priest in 1977.
      He reposed on September 2, 1982, and is buried at the St Herman of Alaska
      Monastery in Platina.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* CONVERSION JOURNEY */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>From Spiritual Seeker to Orthodox Monk</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim's path to Orthodoxy ran through the intellectual currents
      of mid-century America. As a young man he set aside the Protestantism of
      his upbringing and searched for truth in philosophy and the religions of
      the East &mdash; Buddhism and Taoism above all &mdash; studying Chinese
      thought seriously enough to translate from the Tao Te Ching. He was marked
      by a deep dissatisfaction with the secularism and relativism of modern
      culture, which he later analyzed at length in his writing.
    </p>
    <p>
      That search led him, by way of the writings of René Guénon and finally a
      living encounter with the Russian émigré community in San Francisco, to
      the Orthodox Church. Decisive in this was <strong
        >St John Maximovitch</strong
      >, the ROCOR Archbishop of San Francisco, whom Father Seraphim came to
      revere as his spiritual father and who blessed the work he and Gleb
      Podmoshensky would undertake. He was received into the Church in 1962.
    </p>
    <ol class="sr-timeline">
      {
        SERAPHIM_LIFE_TIMELINE.map((t) => (
          <li>
            <span class="sr-tl-when">{t.when}</span>
            <div class="sr-tl-body">
              <h4>{t.title}</h4>
              <p>
                {t.body}
                {t.source && (
                  <a
                    class="sr-src"
                    href={t.source}
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >
                    source ↗
                  </a>
                )}
              </p>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  {/* SPIRITUAL LINEAGE */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Spiritual Lineage</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim received the Orthodox tradition through the Russian Church
      Abroad and, most directly, through <strong>St John Maximovitch</strong>.
      His spirituality drew consciously on the inheritance of nineteenth-century
      Russian Orthodoxy &mdash; particularly the tradition of the Optina Elders,
      whose emphasis on eldership, the Jesus Prayer, and patristic continuity he
      sought to transmit to English-speaking readers. Through his books and the
      Platina brotherhood, that tradition reached a generation of American
      converts.
    </p>
    <div class="sr-lineage" aria-label="Spiritual lineage">
      <div class="sr-lin-node">
        Optina Elders
        <span class="sr-lin-sub">19th-century Russian eldership</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sr-lin-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>
      <div class="sr-lin-node">Russian Orthodox Tradition</div>
      <div class="sr-lin-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>
      <div class="sr-lin-node">
        <a href={withBase("saint/OS-0050")} class="sr-lin-link"
          >St John Maximovitch</a
        >
        <span class="sr-lin-sub">Archbishop of San Francisco (†1966)</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sr-lin-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>
      <div class="sr-lin-node sr-lin-current">
        Father Seraphim Rose
        <span class="sr-lin-sub">Monk and writer of Platina</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sr-lin-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>
      <div class="sr-lin-node">American Orthodox Converts</div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ST HERMAN BROTHERHOOD */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>The St Herman of Alaska Brotherhood</h2>
    <p>
      The St Herman of Alaska Brotherhood was founded in 1963 by Eugene Rose and
      Gleb Podmoshensky, with the blessing of St John Maximovitch, as a
      community of Orthodox booksellers and publishers. Named for the first
      canonized saint of North America, it took as its mission the
      evangelization of the English-speaking world through the printed word:
      making the lives of the saints, the writings of the Fathers, and the
      Orthodox spiritual tradition available in English, including through
      translation of major Orthodox works.
    </p>
    <p>
      From a San Francisco bookstore (opened 1964) the brotherhood grew into the
      monastic community at Platina. Its publishing work continued after Father
      Seraphim's repose in 1982, and the brotherhood remains active in printing,
      translation, and missionary outreach &mdash; the reason it became a
      significant institution in the development of English-speaking Orthodoxy.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* ORTHODOX WORD */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>The Orthodox Word</h2>
    <p>
      The Orthodox Word, a bimonthly magazine, was begun in January 1965 by the
      brotherhood, alongside St Herman Press. Its purpose was to present
      Orthodox Christianity &mdash; the lives of saints, patristic texts in
      translation, and accounts of Orthodox history and spirituality &mdash; to
      an English-speaking readership that had little such material available at
      the time. The magazine became one of the brotherhood's most enduring works
      and continues in publication today.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* MONASTERY */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>St Herman of Alaska Monastery, Platina, California</h2>
    <p>
      In 1969 the brotherhood left the city for the wilderness near Platina, in
      the mountains of northern California; the first monks were tonsured in
      1970, marking the beginning of the St Herman of Alaska Monastery. (Some
      reference works date the monastery's founding to 1968; the monastery's own
      account gives the move in 1969 and the first tonsures in 1970.) The remote
      setting was deliberate &mdash; a place of prayer and ascetic labour apart
      from modern distraction.
    </p>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim is buried at the monastery, on the spot of his last public
      talk, and his grave is a place of pilgrimage. The monastery continues the
      brotherhood's life of prayer together with its publishing and missionary
      outreach.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* WORKS BY */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Works by Father Seraphim Rose</h2>
    <div class="sr-tablewrap">
      <table class="sr-table">
        <thead>
          <tr
            ><th>Title</th><th>Type</th><th>Publication</th><th>Description</th
            ></tr
          >
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            SERAPHIM_WORKS.map((bk) => (
              <tr>
                <td>
                  {bk.source ? (
                    <a
                      href={bk.source}
                      target="_blank"
                      rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    >
                      {bk.title}
                    </a>
                  ) : (
                    bk.title
                  )}
                </td>
                <td>{bk.type}</td>
                <td>
                  {bk.publisher}
                  {bk.year ? `, ${bk.year}` : ""}
                </td>
                <td>{bk.desc}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="sr-fineprint">
      Note: two titles often attributed to Father Seraphim are not his own
      works.
      <em>Raising Them Right</em> is a work of St Theophan the Recluse that Father
      Seraphim translated, and <em>Man: The Target of UFOs?</em> is a confusion with
      his chapter on UFOs within <em
        >Orthodoxy and the Religion of the Future</em
      >; neither is listed above.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* BOOKS ABOUT */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Books About Father Seraphim Rose</h2>
    <div class="sr-tablewrap">
      <table class="sr-table">
        <thead>
          <tr
            ><th>Title</th><th>Author</th><th>Type</th><th>Detail</th><th
              >Significance</th
            ></tr
          >
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {
            SERAPHIM_BOOKS_ABOUT.map((bk) => (
              <tr>
                <td>
                  {bk.source ? (
                    <a
                      href={bk.source}
                      target="_blank"
                      rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    >
                      {bk.title}
                    </a>
                  ) : (
                    bk.title
                  )}
                </td>
                <td>{bk.author}</td>
                <td>{bk.type}</td>
                <td>{bk.detail}</td>
                <td>{bk.desc}</td>
              </tr>
            ))
          }
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* MAJOR THEMES */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Major Themes in His Writings</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim's writings return to a consistent set of concerns, which
      may be set out historically rather than polemically:
    </p>
    <ul class="sr-themes">
      {THEMES.map((t) => <li>{t}</li>)}
    </ul>
    <p>
      Across these themes runs a single argument: that the spiritual crisis of
      the modern West &mdash; which he traced from nihilism through secularism
      to a coming “religion of the future” &mdash; is answered not by novelty
      but by the patristic Christianity preserved in the Orthodox Church. His
      book on the soul after death and his commentary on Genesis applied the
      same patristic lens to the questions of the afterlife and of creation.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* SELECTED TEACHINGS */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Selected Teachings</h2>
    <p class="sr-fineprint">
      Drawn from his published works and letters. Widely-circulated sayings that
      could not be tied to a specific source have been omitted.
    </p>
    {
      quotesByTheme.map((g) => (
        <div class="sr-qgroup">
          <h3>{g.theme}</h3>
          {g.items.map((q) => (
            <blockquote class="sr-quote">
              <p>“{q.text}”</p>
              <cite>{q.work}</cite>
            </blockquote>
          ))}
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </section>

  {/* HISTORICAL SIGNIFICANCE */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim's significance lies chiefly in the field of
      English-language Orthodox publishing. Through The Orthodox Word, St Herman
      Press, and his own books, he helped make the Orthodox spiritual and
      patristic tradition available to readers who had no access to it in their
      own language, at a time when little existed. His apologetic works
      addressed converts and inquirers shaped by modern Western thought, and his
      books have remained continuously in print and widely read in the decades
      since his repose.
    </p>
    <p>
      His influence on Orthodox monasticism in America came through the Platina
      brotherhood and the communities connected to it. Assessments of his
      thought vary, and some of his positions have been debated within Orthodox
      circles; what is not disputed is the scale of his readership and his place
      in the twentieth-century history of Orthodoxy in North America.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* WHY AMERICANS READ */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Why Americans Continue to Read Father Seraphim</h2>
    <p>
      Several features of Father Seraphim's life help explain his enduring
      readership among English-speaking Christians. He was American-born and
      formed by modern Western culture; he confronted directly the questions of
      secularism, relativism, and meaning that occupy that culture; and his own
      search ran through philosophy and the religions of the East before
      arriving at Orthodoxy. Because he wrote in English and from within that
      experience, many later converts have found in his biography a path that
      resembles their own.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* RELATED WITNESSES */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Related Witnesses</h2>
    <ul class="sr-related">
      {
        SERAPHIM_RELATED.map((r) => (
          <li>
            {r.href ? (
              <a href={withBase(r.href)}>{r.name}</a>
            ) : (
              <span class="sr-related-name">{r.name}</span>
            )}
            <span class="sr-related-note"> &mdash; {r.note}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  {/* ORTHODOXY IN AMERICA TIMELINE */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Orthodoxy in America: Father Seraphim's Place in the Story</h2>
    <p>
      Father Seraphim's work belongs to the longer history of Orthodox
      Christianity in North America &mdash; and represents a distinct phase of
      it: the communication of Orthodoxy, in English, to modern Americans.
    </p>
    <ol class="sr-timeline sr-timeline--america">
      {
        SERAPHIM_AMERICA_TIMELINE.map((t) => (
          <li>
            <span class="sr-tl-when">{t.when}</span>
            <div class="sr-tl-body">
              <h4>{t.title}</h4>
              <p>
                {t.body}
                {t.source && (
                  <a
                    class="sr-src"
                    href={t.source}
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >
                    source ↗
                  </a>
                )}
              </p>
              {t.figures && t.figures.length > 0 && (
                <div class="sr-tl-figures">
                  {t.figures.map((f) =>
                    f.href ? (
                      <a class="sr-chip" href={withBase(f.href)}>
                        {f.name}
                      </a>
                    ) : (
                      <span class="sr-chip sr-chip--plain">{f.name}</span>
                    ),
                  )}
                </div>
              )}
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  {/* GALLERY SUGGESTIONS */}
  <section class="sr-sec">
    <h2>Gallery Suggestions</h2>
    <p class="sr-fineprint">
      Recommended imagery for a future illustrated edition of this profile (none
      reproduced here pending licensing and review):
    </p>
    <ul class="sr-gallery">
      {
        SERAPHIM_GALLERY.map((g) => (
          <li>
            <span class="sr-gal-subject">{g.subject}</span>
            <span class="sr-gal-caption">{g.caption}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  {/* SOURCES */}
  <section class="sr-sec sr-sources">
    <h2>Sources</h2>
    <ol>
      {
        SERAPHIM_SOURCES.map((s) => (
          <li>
            <a href={s.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              {s.label}
            </a>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
    <p class="sr-fineprint">
      Additional citations appear inline beside the timelines, tables, and
      bibliographies above. This profile is a historical account compiled from
      the sources listed and remains subject to clergy and source review.
    </p>
  </section>
</article>

<style>
  .sr {
    max-width: 820px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 28px clamp(16px, 4vw, 30px) 80px;
  }
  .sr-back {
    margin-bottom: 22px;
  }
  .sr-back-link {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 6px;
    font-family: var(--text);
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--celest);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .sr-back-link:hover {
    color: var(--byz-deep);
  }

  .sr-head {
    display: flex;
    gap: clamp(16px, 4vw, 30px);
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .sr-portrait {
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .sr-name {
    font-size: clamp(30px, 5vw, 44px);
    color: var(--byz-deep);
    line-height: 1.04;
    margin: 10px 0 4px;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .sr-epithet {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 20px;
    color: var(--celest);
    margin: 0 0 10px;
  }
  .sr-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .sr-role {
    font-family: var(--text);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.16em;
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--gold-deep);
  }
  .sr-dot {
    width: 4px;
    height: 4px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--celest);
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .sr-years {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--celest);
  }
  .sr-place {
    font-size: 14.5px;
    color: var(--celest);
    margin: 8px 0 0;
  }

  .sr-notice {
    background: #f4ecdd;
    border: 1px solid var(--gold-deep);
    border-left-width: 4px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 14px 18px;
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: #5a4a2a;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }
  .sr-notice strong {
    color: var(--gold-deep);
  }

  .sr-sec {
    margin: 0 0 38px;
  }
  .sr-sec h2 {
    font-size: clamp(20px, 3vw, 25px);
    color: var(--byz-deep);
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 14px;
    padding-bottom: 8px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--gold-soft);
  }
  .sr-sec h3 {
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--byz-deep);
    margin: 18px 0 8px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  }
  .sr-sec p {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.72;
    color: #2b2b2b;
    margin: 0 0 16px;
  }
  .sr-fineprint {
    font-size: 13.5px !important;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--celest);
    line-height: 1.55 !important;
  }
  .sr-fineprint a {
    color: var(--byz-deep);
  }

  .sr-lineage {
    margin: 20px auto;
    max-width: 460px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .sr-lin-node {
    background: linear-gradient(168deg, #27537f 0%, #1e426a 100%);
    border: 1px solid var(--gold-deep);
    border-radius: 10px;
    color: var(--ivory);
    padding: 12px 16px;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 16px;
  }
  .sr-lin-current {
    background: linear-gradient(168deg, #2f6a4a 0%, #234f38 100%);
  }
  .sr-lin-link {
    color: var(--gold-soft);
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .sr-lin-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
  .sr-lin-sub {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    color: #cdd9e6;
    margin-top: 3px;
  }
  .sr-lin-current .sr-lin-sub {
    color: #cfe6da;
  }
  .sr-lin-arrow {
    color: var(--gold-deep);
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin: 4px 0;
  }

  .sr-timeline {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 18px 0 8px;
    padding: 0;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--gold-soft);
  }
  .sr-timeline li {
    position: relative;
    padding: 0 0 20px 22px;
  }
